===Noun===
{{en-noun|''Latin plural'' '''[[oxymora]]''', ''Anglicized plural'' '''[[oxymorons]]'''}}

# A [[figure of speech]] in which two words of opposing meanings are used together deliberately for effect. A famous example is Milton, ''Paradise Lost'', Book 1, ll. 63-4:
:::No light, but rather '''darkness visible'''
:::Serv'd only to discover sights of woe 
# {{context|loosely}} A [[contradiction in terms]].
# A paradoxical juxtaposition of two seemingly contradictory words.

====Usage notes====
* Traditionally, the noun {{term||oxymoron}} refers to the figure of speech, wherein the contradiction is deliberate. The use of the term to refer to unintentional contradictions in terms is considered incorrect by some speakers and writers, and is perhaps best avoided in certain contexts. (See the [[w:oxymoron|Wikipedia article]].)

